The world only knows that Nepal have the highest mountains in the world. but Pakistan is only true rival with Nepal in term of the highest mountains but there are certain features that Nepal don't have like
Pakistan have 5 8000M peaks out of 14
Pakistan have the three highest mountains ranges which collide at the single place Karakoram, Himalaya and Hindukush
the highest peak of Himalaya in Pakistan is nanga Parbat (8126m) second largest peak of Himalaya outside Nepal.
the highest peak of Karakoram range and the second-highest mountain in the world K2(8611m)
the highest peak of Hindukush is Tirichmir (7700m) which is in Pakistan and it is 33 highest mountain in the world.
Pakistan have 45 highest peaks out of 100 in the world.
Pakistan have 150 peaks above 7000m and there are countless peaks above the 6000,5000 and 4000m in height.
Pakistan is one of the few countries in the world that have hot deserts, cold deserts, delta, rivers, vast plains,, vast snowy and green mountains, vast barren and rigid mountains, islands, sunny beaches and vast plains.
Pakistan have five season winter, summer, autumn, spring and rainy monsoon season. it is one of the few countries where you can find snow, hot summer at the same time all year around. you can feel 40c and -40c temperature at the same in any time year around
Pakistan have glaciers than any country in Europe. longest glaciers outside the polar region are in Pakistan. the glacier area of Pakistan is more than 15000sqkm which is one-third of the area.
We have the oldest history of the world which predates Egypt and Mesopotamia in history and is estimated around 8000 years old

What elevations were you hiking in?  I'm from low elevation Minnesota and only hiked to over 12,000 Ft or 3,600 meters two times, and to 11,000 once.  I had a very bad headache and had to hike back down, and even after an attempt to first acclimate at 7,300 for a week.  I'm now 65 and wondering if people my age have done this trek.  I'm thinking that with guides and all the food and cooking that it is very expensive to do this, right?  It's amazing that you are so young and speak their language (Urdu?) too. Is this better than hiking to base camp for Everest?  I'm thinking Everest is so much more popular that it must not be as exciting with so many hiking at once there.  Did the porters carry your supplies too so all you had was a small day pack?  Did they provide the tents too?  I like the remoteness of your trip too!  Thanks for sharing your talent and sense of adventure!
